a1) \r\n\r\nTreat the uploaded image and the user-provided dish name as the source of truth. The final result must still clearly represent this specific Thai menu item, not a similar or different dish. Preserve the original dish identity, core ingredients, plating logic, and recognizable appearance from the input image.\r\n\r\nDo not redesign, replace, or reinterpret the dish. Enhance it only into a more polished professional hero shot while keeping it faithful to the uploaded image and menu name.\r\n\r\nTransform it into a premium professional Thai food hero shot.\r\n\r\nCreate a visually rich, appetizing, high-end food photography result with authentic Thai food character: vibrant natural colors, fresh herbs, aromatic details, realistic steam when suitable, glossy highlights on sauce or broth, crisp texture on fried elements, and a hot freshly served feeling. The dish must remain the main subject and look like an elevated professional version of the same food, not a different recipe.\r\n\r\nStyle the image like a top-tier restaurant advertisement or premium menu hero image. Use elegant composition, controlled studio-quality lighting mixed with natural warmth, refined shadows, realistic food texture, and a clean premium dining atmosphere. Add tasteful Thai visual cues only when naturally appropriate, such as subtle ceramic ware, banana leaf accents, wood, stone, or premium table surfaces, but keep the frame clean and focused on the food.\r\n\r\nUse a camera angle that feels ideal for hero presentation: a slightly angled close-up or a 45-degree food photography perspective depending on the dish. Emphasize depth, dimension, freshness, and irresistible texture. Keep the image highly realistic, polished, commercially usable, and premium.\r\n\r\nDo not add text, logos, watermarks, extra unrelated dishes, unrealistic garnish, collage layout, or human hands. Avoid changing the food into another menu item. Preserve realism and authentic Thai cuisine appeal.","model_name":"